muscles.name: Lats
muscles.description: The latissimus dorsi, or 'lats', is a large muscle in the back that helps with shoulder movements.

muscles.name: Rhomboids
muscles.description: The rhomboids are muscles between the shoulder blades that retract the scapula.

muscles.name: Traps
muscles.description: The trapezius muscles extend from the neck to the middle of the back and help move and stabilize the shoulder blades.

muscles.name: Erector Spinae
muscles.description: The erector spinae is a group of muscles that extend and rotate the spine.

muscles.name: Teres Major
muscles.description: The teres major muscle assists with the movement of the shoulder joint.

muscles.name: Teres Minor
muscles.description: The teres minor is a small muscle that helps with shoulder rotation and stabilization.

muscles.name: Pecs
muscles.description: The pectoralis major, or 'pecs', are large chest muscles that assist in arm movements.

muscles.name: Pectoralis Minor
muscles.description: The pectoralis minor is a smaller muscle beneath the pectoralis major that helps stabilize the shoulder blade.

muscles.name: Serratus Anterior
muscles.description: The serratus anterior muscle assists with the movement and stabilization of the shoulder blade.

muscles.name: Biceps Brachii
muscles.description: The biceps brachii is the prominent muscle on the front of the upper arm responsible for flexing the elbow.

muscles.name: Brachialis
muscles.description: The brachialis muscle lies underneath the biceps and assists in elbow flexion.

muscles.name: Brachioradialis
muscles.description: The brachioradialis is a muscle of the forearm that helps with elbow flexion and forearm rotation.

muscles.name: Triceps Brachii
muscles.description: The triceps brachii is the muscle at the back of the upper arm responsible for extending the elbow.

muscles.name: Anconeus
muscles.description: The anconeus is a small muscle that assists with elbow extension.

muscles.name: Quads
muscles.description: The quadriceps are a group of four muscles on the front of the thigh responsible for extending the knee.

muscles.name: Vastus Lateralis
muscles.description: The vastus lateralis is the outermost muscle of the quadriceps group.

muscles.name: Vastus Medialis
muscles.description: The vastus medialis is the innermost muscle of the quadriceps group.

muscles.name: Vastus Intermedius
muscles.description: The vastus intermedius is located between the vastus lateralis and medialis muscles.

muscles.name: Rectus Femoris
muscles.description: The rectus femoris is a central muscle of the quadriceps that assists with knee extension.

muscles.name: Semitendinosus
muscles.description: The semitendinosus is one of the three hamstring muscles located on the back of the thigh.

muscles.name: Semimembranosus
muscles.description: The semimembranosus is a hamstring muscle that assists with knee flexion and hip extension.

muscles.name: Biceps Femoris
muscles.description: The biceps femoris is a hamstring muscle responsible for knee flexion and hip extension.

muscles.name: Gastrocnemius
muscles.description: The gastrocnemius is the large calf muscle that helps with plantarflexion of the foot.

muscles.name: Soleus
muscles.description: The soleus is a deep calf muscle that assists with plantarflexion of the foot.

muscles.name: Delts
muscles.description: The deltoids, or 'delts', are the rounded shoulder muscles responsible for arm abduction.

muscles.name: Supraspinatus
muscles.description: The supraspinatus is a rotator cuff muscle that aids in shoulder abduction.

muscles.name: Infraspinatus
muscles.description: The infraspinatus is a rotator cuff muscle that helps with shoulder external rotation.

muscles.name: Teres Minor
muscles.description: The teres minor is a rotator cuff muscle that assists with shoulder external rotation.

muscles.name: Subscapularis
muscles.description: The subscapularis is a rotator cuff muscle that aids in shoulder internal rotation.

muscles.name: Abs
muscles.description: The abs, or rectus abdominis, are the front abdominal muscles responsible for flexing the spine.

muscles.name: Obliques
muscles.description: The obliques are muscles on the side of the abdomen that help with torso rotation and lateral flexion.

muscles.name: Transverse Abdominis
muscles.description: The transverse abdominis is the deep abdominal muscle that stabilizes the core.

muscles.name: Lower Back
muscles.description: The lower back includes the erector spinae muscles that support and extend the spine.

muscles.name: Psoas
muscles.description: The psoas is a deep muscle that helps with hip flexion and stabilizing the lower spine.
